Project Request: Automated IOC-Driven Detection Rule Generation via DFIR-IRIS API Integration
Background & Problem Statement
During digital forensics and incident response (DFIR) engagements, Indicators of Compromise (IOCs) are continuously discovered and documented throughout the lifecycle of a case. Our team uses DFIR-IRIS as the central collaborative platform for this documentation — it houses timelines, findings, and engagement-specific IOCs as they are identified.
The problem is that these IOCs currently live passively in DFIR-IRIS. They are documented, but that documentation does not automatically translate into actionable detection capability. As a result:

Analysts must manually extract IOCs and hand-craft detection rules, which is time-consuming and error-prone.
When new evidence arrives mid-engagement (e.g., additional disk images received weeks after initial triage), previously documented IOCs are not automatically applied to the new evidence — creating gaps in forensic coverage.
There is no centralized, reusable repository of detection rule files derived from engagement-specific IOCs. The intelligence sits in the platform but cannot be easily operationalized elsewhere across the organization.


Proposed Solution
We are requesting API access to DFIR-IRIS to enable an automated pipeline that converts documented IOCs into detection rules and continuously applies them to evidence as engagements evolve.
The workflow is as follows:

IOC Ingestion — An analyst enters an IOC into DFIR-IRIS during the normal course of an engagement (no change to existing workflow).
Automated Rule Generation — A script leverages the DFIR-IRIS API to pull down IOCs from the engagement and automatically generate detection rules in a standardized format (e.g., YARA, Sigma, or another target format).
Continuous Scanning — The generated rules are operationalized and used to scan evidence at configurable intervals using the scanner of our choosing. As new evidence is added to an engagement, it is automatically scanned against all existing IOCs — ensuring nothing is missed.


Why This Matters
Engagements rarely unfold in a single, discrete evidence package. A customer may deliver an initial disk image in January, then provide additional systems or logs in February. Under the current workflow, IOCs from the January work must be manually re-applied to the February evidence. This introduces the risk of oversight, especially as engagements grow in scope.
This automated pipeline ensures that forensic coverage compounds over time — every IOC entered into DFIR-IRIS, at any point in the engagement, becomes a detection rule that is applied retroactively and prospectively to all evidence.

Complementary Capabilities Already in Place
Our team already has tooling for mass image mounting across various filesystem formats, which enables large-scale IOC scanning across multiple images simultaneously. This is a significant force multiplier — the only missing piece is the upstream ability to programmatically pull IOCs from DFIR-IRIS as they are entered, which is what the API access enables.

Additional Organizational Benefit: A Living IOC Rule Repository
A secondary benefit of this project is the creation of a persistent, engagement-indexed repository of detection rule files. Currently, IOC intelligence is siloed within DFIR-IRIS. This project would produce tangible rule files (YARA signatures, Sigma rules, etc.) that:

Can be version-controlled and audited.
Can be rapidly deployed or shared across other teams and tooling within the organization.
Extend the value of engagement-specific findings beyond the immediate case.


Access Requested
DFIR-IRIS API access (read permissions on IOC/case data) to enable the automated integration described above.
